Free body diagram and static finite element analysis of the human tibia
Bhaskar Kumar Madeti*
Department of Mechanical Engineering, Gayatri Vidya Parishad College of Engineering (A), Visakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh, India Email: madetibhaskar@rediffmail.com *Corresponding author
Chalamalasetti Srinivasa Rao and Bollapragada S.K. Sundara Siva Rao
Department of Mechanical Engineering, AU College of Engineering (A), Andhra University, Visakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh, India Email: csr_auce@yahoo.co.in Email: bsk_sundara@yahoo.co.in
Abstract: Static analysis on tibia is performed for three different postures of humans (standing, staircase ascent and descent) by drawing a free body diagram. A model of the tibia bone is created in CATIA software and is imported to ANSYS. Obtained values during standing and stair ascent and descent are incorporated in finite element analysis. The stress distribution and deformation made in the human bone tibia are observed.
Keywords: finite element analysis; nodes; meshing; tetrahedron; axial compressive stress; deformation; tibia.
Reference to this paper should be made as follows: Madeti, B.K., Rao, C.S. and Sundara Siva Rao, B.S.K. (2015) ‘Free body diagram and static finite element analysis of the human tibia’, Int. J. Biomedical Engineering and Technology, Vol. 18, No. 3, pp.290–299.
