1 Introduction
In developing models such as a model of the tibia bone, the first step is to generate computer models of the bones. The finite element formulations of contact characteristics have been used by biomechanics investigators to evaluate relative shift of the bone. The elasticity of the bone is likely to be a factor influencing bone growth in the tibia. Static analysis was performed and material properties of bone were assumed linear, isotropic and inhomogeneous. Characteristics of the bone can be found underwater as well (Zhang et al., 2014). The rate of application of finite element analysis to the evaluation of stresses in bones and to the fracture fixation devices has increased drastically in the last decade. Evaluation of stresses in bones helps in defining the effects of the constituent properties of the bone on its macroscopic behaviour. The application of the finite element technique to orthopaedic problems is different from its application to structural problems in that, in orthopaedics, a lot is dependent on the nature of the individual living tissues involved. Material properties are not as predominantly defined as in structural problems. Both geometric characteristics and material properties play a very important role in results that are reached. Moreover, it is absolutely necessary that a multidisciplinary team (both engineers and doctors) be involved in the study of orthopaedic.
In recent days, replacement with implants in the joints of the human body is taking place. Materials used for implants are not much closer to the bone material (Baldwin et al., 2012; Halloran et al., 2005; Burny et al., 2000). Mechanical analysis should be done so that the exact forces may be determined, and depending upon the forces involved, suitable materials can be used. Owing to excessive loads transmitted to the bone, the ligaments may fail and may be exposed to severe pain (Meyer and Haut, 2005; Woo et al., 2006; Li et al., 1998). Implants may be designed in such a way that it reduces the muscle forces. With the mechanical analysis, muscle forces can also be obtained. Earlier authors used various optimisation techniques to reduce muscle forces (Pedotti et al., 1978; Challis and Kerwin, 1993). In the present paper, the analysis is done by reverse engineering the muscle, and axial compressive forces are obtained later the axial compressive loads are applied on the tibia bone in various postures in ANSYS; thereafter, stress distribution are found. Here due to abduction and adduction movement of the knee, it is difficult to apply forces in the tibia bone; these loads are of varying loads (Harrington, 1983).
Computer Tomography (CT) scans or Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) constitutes the input data required for modelling the human parts such as bones. Using these data we can make FEM model (Pena et al., 2006; Devika and Arumaikkannu, 2011) incorporating the material properties and the loading conditions, which yield required results. Since bone is an anisotropic material the properties in three directions must be used. In the present work, we got the dimensions through X-ray and MRI scans. We used the anisotropic properties of the tibia bone. The model is first created in CATIA software;

