The above equations are obtained from Figure 1. By solving these equations, forces acting on tibia are attained. Consider a male of 60 kg body mass. Then, m1 = 2.1 kg, R = 60  9.81 and we also found that α = 40° and the corresponding θ = 40° by substituting these values in the above equations. Consider a male with body mass 60 kg, so m1 = 2.1 kg; R = 60 * 9.81; we found that α = 40° and the corresponding θ = 220° by substituting these values in the above equations. The axial compressive force on tibia is 1800 N force acting on the knee during staircase ascent, while descending forces acting on the knee is 2500 N; in the standing posture, half the weight of the person is considered (Madeti et al., 2014b). Different combinations of various forces may obtained by taking the best values in the finite element analysis.

