5 Results and discussion Results obtained from the finite element analysis are the maximum compressive stress on the tibia during the three postures of standing, staircase ascent and staircase descent: 5.6, 11 and 17 MPa, respectively. The maximum deformation occurring in the three cases are 0.49, 1.489 and 2.004 mm, respectively, for 600N person. For all these cases, more stresses are developed in the lower portion of the tibia. We have considered Von Mises effective stress because the bone is a ductile material. The Tresca stress is usually used for brittle materials.
6 Conclusions The conclusions of the study are as follows:  The axial compressive force and muscle force can be obtained by drawing free body
diagram of the human knee.  During stair ascent, less axial compressive force is required, while descending the
axial compressive is more.  An FEA analysis of the tibia with this stress distribution is clearly identified
throughout the surface of the tibia.  By knowing the maximum stresses, suitable replacement components may be
designed. Materials can be selected, which are close to the material properties of the bone.

